Document: AcceptDialog
Path: godot/classes/class_acceptdialog.rst
Summary: Methods for managing buttons, labels, and text input in AcceptDialog.

Method: add_button(text: String, right: bool = false, action: String = "") → Button
Adds a button with label text and custom action to the dialog. If action is non-empty, pressing the button emits the custom_action signal with the specified action string. The right parameter controls button alignment. Use remove_button() to remove the button.

Method: add_cancel_button(name: String) → Button
Adds a cancel button with the specified label. The button emits the canceled signal when pressed. Use remove_button() to remove the button.

Method: get_label() → Label
Returns the internal label node used for built-in text. Warning: Removing or freeing this node may cause a crash. To hide it, modify the visible property of the node or its children.

Method: get_ok_button() → Button
Returns the internal OK button instance. Warning: Removing or freeing this node may cause a crash. To hide it, modify the visible property of the node or its children.

Method: register_text_enter(line_edit: LineEdit)
Registers a LineEdit instance. Pressing Enter in the line edit will accept the dialog.

Method: remove_button(button: Button)
Removes the specified button from the dialog without freeing it. The button must have been added via add_button() or add_cancel_button(). After removal, the button no longer emits dialog signals.
---CHUNK---
Document: AcceptDialog
Path: godot/classes/class_acceptdialog.rst
Summary: Theme properties controlling button sizing and panel styling in AcceptDialog.

buttons_min_height (int): 0. The minimum height of each button in the bottom row (such as OK/Cancel) in pixels. This can be increased to make buttons with short texts easier to click/tap.

buttons_min_width (int): 0. The minimum width of each button in the bottom row (such as OK/Cancel) in pixels. This can be increased to make buttons with short texts easier to click/tap.

buttons_separation (int): 10. The size of the vertical space between the dialog's content and the button row.

panel (StyleBox): The panel that fills the background of the window.